From 399512cef49efc5312ffd4fef4e5dea47d3423e5 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: utzcoz <utzcoz@outlook.com>
Date: Mon, 13 Jul 2026 00:10:32 +0800
Subject: [PATCH 10/10] vr: allocate the WebXR shared buffer via Ozone/GBM
 (Linux)

The XR utility process hand-allocated the intermediate image as a LINEAR DMA-BUF in Vulkan and
exported it. The NVIDIA proprietary driver cannot render into that across the process boundary:
LINEAR is not GL-renderable, and a hand-picked renderable modifier hangs the GPU (VK_ERROR_-
DEVICE_LOST / GL_GUILTY_CONTEXT_RESET), because the XR-process Vulkan cannot pick a modifier the
GPU-process GL/EGL importer accepts.

Instead, allocate the buffer the way normal Chromium rendering does: the GPU process allocates an
Ozone/GBM native pixmap -- which runs the driver's own create/export/re-import modifier
validation loop, including the explicit NVIDIA blocklist in gbm_wrapper.cc -- via
SharedImageInterface::CreateSharedImage with BufferUsage::SCANOUT, and the XR process imports the
returned DMA-BUF into Vulkan (handling multi-plane modifiers such as AMD DCC) as the RenderLayer
blit source. Falls back to the previous LINEAR export path where GBM native pixmaps are
unavailable (e.g. X11 DRI3 render nodes, headless Ozone), so no configuration regresses.

The in-headset overlay-UI image (GetExportedOverlayImage) is allocated the same way and imported
into Vulkan as a SAMPLED image, since NVIDIA GL cannot render into a LINEAR overlay import either
(it reported GL_FRAMEBUFFER_INCOMPLETE_ATTACHMENT on the XR_COMPOSITING context).

Verified on AMD/RADV Wayland: base and overlay images render through a GBM 3-plane DCC modifier
with no fallback and no framebuffer-incomplete errors.
